      <h2>Complete Guide to Backup Generators in West Michigan</h2>
      <p>
        West Michigan loses power to wind, ice, and lake-effect storms more often than most U.S. regions — the lakeshore
        from Holland through Grand Haven sees multi-hour outages multiple times each winter, and 24–72 hour outages
        every few years during major ice events. A standby generator turns those outages from a crisis into an
        inconvenience: the lights stay on, the sump pump runs, the furnace blower works, and the contents of the freezer
        survive.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide covers everything a homeowner or facility manager needs to evaluate a generator install: sizing,
        fuel, transfer switching, code, and the West Michigan specifics that drive most of the decision.
      </p>

      <h3>Whole-Home vs Portable: The First Decision</h3>
      <p>
        Whole-home (standby) generators run automatically, are fueled by propane or natural gas, and can power your
        entire panel for days or weeks. Portable generators cost a fraction of the install price but require manual
        setup every outage, run on gasoline with limited shelf life, and only cover selected essential circuits.
      </p>
      <p>
        For most West Michigan homeowners with well pumps, sump pumps, home offices, or medical equipment, whole-home is
        the right call. For homeowners with rare brief outages and minimal critical loads, portable plus an
        <a href="/glossary/automatic-transfer-switch">interlock kit</a> is the cost-conscious legal option. See
        <a href="/blog/whole-home-vs-portable-generator"
          >whole-home vs portable generator: which makes sense in West Michigan</a
        > for the full comparison.
      </p>

      <h3>Sizing: How Many kW You Actually Need</h3>
      <p>
        Generator capacity is rated in <a href="/glossary/kva-vs-kw">kilowatts (kW)</a>. Most 2,000 sq ft Michigan homes
        need a 14–22 kW whole-home generator. A 3,000+ sq ft home with central AC, electric range, and an EV charger
        typically needs 22–26 kW. The deciding factor is simultaneous load, not square footage — and the sizing decision
        should follow a documented <a href="/glossary/load-calculation">NEC Article 220 load calculation</a>, not a
        square-footage rule of thumb.
      </p>
      <p>
        Common undersizing mistakes: ignoring well pumps and sump pumps (motor inrush is 6–8× running watts),
        underestimating central AC startup, and forgetting future EV chargers. See
        <a href="/blog/how-to-size-a-whole-home-generator">how to size a whole-home generator for a Michigan home</a>
        for the exact math.
      </p>

      <h3>Transfer Switching: How the Generator Connects to Your House</h3>
      <p>
        You cannot legally or safely plug a generator into a wall outlet. Backfeeding power onto the utility grid can
        kill the lineman trying to restore service, destroys your generator when utility power returns, and violates NEC
        702.5. Every generator install requires one of:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Automatic transfer switch (ATS)</strong> — the standard for whole-home installs. Senses outage, starts
          the generator, switches the panel over, switches back when utility returns. See
          <a href="/blog/automatic-transfer-switch-explained"
            >what an automatic transfer switch does (and why you need one)</a
          >.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Manual transfer switch</strong> — for portables. You flip selected circuits over by hand.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Generator interlock kit</strong> — code-approved sliding bracket on the panel. The cheapest legal option
          for portable installs. Still requires a licensed electrician and a permit.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Fuel: Natural Gas vs Propane vs Gasoline</h3>
      <p>
        Whole-home generators run on either natural gas (if the house is plumbed for it) or propane. Natural gas is the
        best option — no tank, no refueling, indefinite runtime. Propane runs about 4 days at half load on a 500-gallon
        tank for a 22 kW generator. Gasoline (portables only) becomes a logistics problem in multi-day events: stored
        gas goes stale, station pumps lose power, and carrying cans gets old fast.
      </p>

      <h3>Sizing Up: Panel + Service Coordination</h3>
      <p>
        Many whole-home generator installs are paired with a <a href="/panel-upgrades">panel upgrade</a>, especially
        when the existing service is 100 amp or shows wear. A 200 amp service-rated automatic transfer switch can double
        as your main panel disconnect, giving you one cleaner integrated install rather than two parallel services.
        Adding an EV charger? See
        <a href="/blog/do-i-need-a-panel-upgrade-for-an-ev-charger">do I need a panel upgrade for an EV charger?</a>
      </p>

      <h3>Permits and Inspections in Michigan</h3>
      <p>
        Standby generator installs require an electrical permit (from your AHJ) and a mechanical or plumbing permit (for
        the fuel line). Final inspection covers both the electrical tie-in and the fuel connection. We pull and close
        out both permits as part of the install — no homeowner paperwork.
      </p>

      <h3>What Maintenance Actually Looks Like</h3>
      <p>
        Modern standby generators run a self-test once per week (under load for a brief window). Annual professional
        service includes oil and filter change, spark plugs, air filter, battery test, and a load-bank test to verify
        full output. Most units last 20–25 years with this routine. See
        <a href="/blog/blog-generator-readiness">winter generator readiness: backup power tips</a> for the seasonal checklist.
      </p>

      <h3>West Michigan Specifics</h3>
      <p>
        Lakeshore communities (Holland, Grand Haven, Saugatuck) see more frequent and longer outages than inland areas
        due to lake-effect wind. Generator install priority on the lakeshore is usually whole-home over portable for
        that reason. Inland Hudsonville, Byron Center, and Ada see fewer outages but longer ice-storm events when they
        do come. Permit timelines vary by AHJ from same-week to 2-week turnaround.
      </p>
